Chapter One
Kolkata
At Itanium time, 4:30 in the morning. Kolkata disliked waking up so early. Mainly because he had to wake up the rest of the platoon. He quietly got out of bed, put on his combat uniform, and slipped on his flak jacket, tidied up his belongings from the storage cabinet, carefully picked up a small special box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder, hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. The helmet was equipped with a full set of gear, including a respirator, goggles, and other necessary items. He checked the ammunition pouches before quietly walking out of the barracks, his boots making squelching and crunching sounds on the mud and ice.
He pulled out a lighter from his jacket pocket and a cigarette from another pocket. After lighting the cigarette, he took a gentle puff, then opened the door. In the past week, he had strained his brain to wake up his subordinates. He no longer used the preset alarm clock because half the time it didn't go off, and all that came out of the loudspeaker was a faint buzzing sound.
"Time to wake them up?" Kolkata turned around, seeing Lieutenant Nemiche approaching.
"Yes."
"Time to ask how you plan to do it this time?"
Kolkata hadn't even had a chance to answer when the door opened, and Harris, Kreis, and the others rushed out, all dressed and ready to go.
"Good morning," Kreis said.
"What was it that woke you up?" Kolkata asked.
"First, we'd rather not see what method you'll use to wake everyone up. Secondly, the first squad to get up gets to eat breakfast first," replied Private Ravik. "You know, those breakfasts are terrible."
Kolkata said, "You're right, Private Ravik." He reached out and flipped the switch. The barracks erupted into a loud, ear-piercing alarm. He heard men shouting loudly inside, accompanied by the sound of frantic footsteps.
"Good heavens, Valturi," Lieutenant Nemiche said. "I thought they should've learned to wake up with you by now."
"But my comrades from boot camp have done it," Kolkata said, nodding towards Harris, Kreis, and Ravik. "But come to think of it, their sergeant and platoon sergeant know to wake up before the soldiers do."
Several seconds later, the rest of the platoon's soldiers rushed out. They were all dressed and ready to go. Some of the new recruits looked bleary-eyed, while others seemed thoroughly annoyed.
"Good morning, everyone," Kolkata said, his voice full of cheer.
"Excuse me, sir, but why did you have to wake us up that way?"
"Because those regular alarm clocks are just junk anyway, and Daybreak never sleeps in."
"Take your personal gear," Kolkata continued. As a lieutenant and deputy commander of the platoon, it was his duty to assist Lieutenant Bordin Shao in supervising and leading the platoon. "We won't be back. Sergeant and Lieutenants, give your men and yourselves 15 minutes to do a final check and bring out the rations you'll need today."
Members of Exodus platoon quickly dispersed, part of the 2nd Assault Brigade of the 2nd Army Group. They were previously two independent platoons, Cohort and Dagger, before being merged. This was an elite platoon, and Kolkata felt ambivalent about being promoted to lieutenant, for a variety of reasons.
Lieutenant Kolkata and Sergeant Nemiche walked side by side down the well-lit road of the base, the roadside lights powered by generators, mostly red in color, designed to help them evade enemy bombers.
"New day, new hell for the vanguard," Nemiche said with a chuckle. "Where are they sending us this time?"
"Outside Ianlos, at some forward base, we're being sent to support the ground assault," Kolkata said, taking a drag on his cigarette. He was a bit annoyed with Kreis for getting him hooked on smoking, but a year of endless battles had taken its toll, so he said nothing.
"Good grief, the front's in a tight spot," Nemiche whispered. "All the news coming out of here is 'support the war, aid Kurghan frontline' - what about sending some help to the Harlan frontline instead?"
"Good job, brother," Kolkata said, flicking the cigarette butt into the mud. "We're moving with the First Armored Platoon, no walking involved. Shao should be there."
"Shao will have us ride with the First Armored Platoon?" Nemiche asked in surprise.
"Yes, to be honest, he's not as bad as I imagined. I mean, he's not great, but he's not unbearable either."
"Alright, listen up, men. Exodus, all units, complete the mission and report to the west vehicle depot. We'll be departing at 05:00 with the First Armored Platoon."
Every few seconds, he received a response from the squad leaders. Harris, Kreis, and Ravik, who were all low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they first arrived, had been close friends since their basic training on Earth. It felt like it had been years since Kolkata had met them, even though it had only been less than two years. They were all squad leaders now, but since the first sergeant had been shot by a Daybreak sniper a week ago and was medically discharged, Kreis had taken over as second squad leader.
As they walked to the vehicle depot, Lieutenant Kolkata and Lieutenant Nemiche's eyes fell on approximately eight Chronos main battle tanks and four Scythe armored cars. The crew members were rushing around, ensuring their war machines were in order. Lieutenant Kolkata quickly spotted Lieutenant Shao, who was standing with the commander of the armored platoon, and they walked up to him. As they approached, Lieutenant Shao looked at them and greeted them, his usual stoic face showing no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemiche, Lieutenant Valturi,..." he said, slowing his pace, Lieutenant Shao looked at Kolkata's pistol holster, then raised his head. "Is the platoon ready to move yet?"
